NSW: Fisheries investigate Sydney rock oyster parasite
----------------------
Fisheries are trying to unlock the secrets of a parasite which could
threaten Sydney's rock oyster population. The parasite, QX, is spreading
across waterways in and around Sydney, but at this stage very little is
known about it. "It has caused substantial deaths in the Georges and Tweed
estuaries but not in others, and it doesn't effect other aquatic animals,
it's quite bizarre", a spokeswoman from the fisheries office said today.

The most recent information shows the parasite, QX, which is harmless to
humans, has doubled its number of locations. "Latest tests have revealed QX
is present in estuaries in Merimbula, Wagonga, Tuross, Clyde, Port
Stephens, Wallis Lake, and Hastings," director of NSW Fisheries, Steve Dunn
said in a statement

"Previously, QX had only been identified in 5 estuaries in NSW -- Georges,
Richmond, Tweed, Brunswick and Clarence." NSW Fisheries is working with
scientists from the state's oyster growers, Macquarie University and the
Queensland Museum to solve the parasite mystery.

"There are several unanswered questions, including; is QX in all estuaries,
where did it come from and what triggers an outbreak," Steve Dunn said. Mr
Dunn said tests suggest QX could exist in the gills of Sydney rock oysters
without causing any harm, however once it moved into their gut some die.

"NSW Fisheries spent [Australian] $100 000 on scientific monitoring last
year, and we expect to spend a similar amount this year," Mr Dunn said.

"Over one million dollars has been spent in the last 10 years to come up
with disease-resistant and faster-growing oysters," he said.

