[The parasite responsible for the oyster mortality reported is _Marteilia
sydneyi_, the causative agent of QX disease, a protozoan (_Paramyxea_)
pathogen of the commercial rock oyster in Australia (_Saccostrea
commercialis_).

_M. sydneyi_ has been causing mortality in oysters in culture in southern
Queensland and northern NSW for many years. Management of the disease may
be through moving oysters from susceptible sites (the brackish, estuarine
areas) to QX-free sites, which are generally more sandy. The oysters are
most susceptible during the summer (December - May). Water quality
(including less than optimal pH) may have a significant impact on the
immune system of oysters, and result in increased susceptibility/mortality
in affected populations of oysters. - Mod.TG]
